text:
THOUGHTS ON RAP MUSIC

Music is a beautiful blend of order and chaos. The beat is order. It is predicatble, and after the first 10-20 second, you “get the beat” without having to know the lyrics. The lyrics represent chaos and they are unpredictable (of course until we memorize them). The harmonious blend is what makes music addictive. The beat is order, the lyrics are chaos — and you need both to make a masterpiece. 

Why do some people think certain music is “bad.” The generation behind me (my parents) despise rap in any shape or form, even if the message is “good”. It’s like they just can get past the fact that it often focuses on trauma and overcoming adversity in the world, perhaps they cannot relate? The reality is that I don’t relate to a lot of rap either, but I like it because the beats are straight heat/fire, the flow patterns and play on words are so clever, and the messages express the full range of human emotion (excitement, happiness, anger, sadness, fear, joy, etc)

Isn’t music just an art form like any other? Why are we prosecuting artists for lyrics in their song, its just a song and a way of expression, some of it may be true, but that does not mean it is all true. 

Theater — Shakepear’s playwrights had far more inappropriate language but that is an okay art form. 
Acting — Hollywood movies have actors killing other people, but it’s just a movie and we can separate a movie from reality, right?
Painting — Have you ever seen “The Garden of Earthly Delights” by Renaissance artist, Bosch — we can appreciate that as art

These rappers are literally just artists and have creative minds and music is an outlet for their thoughts. they even have STAGE names. Like Drake’s name is AUBREY, most people know that right? 

My guess is rap has been stigmatized because white people don’t want to listen to the struggles or triumphs of black people, and they disguise their agenda by saying it has poo poo pee pee naught words and thats inappropriate. Is it? It is not self-evident to me why that would be inappropriate. Do the movies you see have  “inappropriate words?” You don’t have to like or enjoy rap. But just realize that you disdain to it likely stems from ignorance and a refusal to see it for what it is — art
